 Deci$ion Question Bank
STUDENT PROFILE - 20 QUESTIONS
Question 1: A classmate offers to share exam answers through a secret chat group that 'everyone' uses.
A) Refuse and report the cheating ring to school authorities (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Refuse to join but don't report it to avoid being labeled a snitch (Integrity: +3, Public Trust: +2, Sustainability: +1)
C) Join the group but promise yourself you won't actually use the answers (Integrity: 0, Public Trust: -1, Sustainability: -1)
D) Join and use the answers since 'everyone does it' (Integrity: -3, Public Trust: -3, Sustainability: -3)
Question 2: You're running out of time on a paper and find a perfect essay online that you could paraphrase.
A) Ask your professor for an extension and explain your situation honestly (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Use the essay as inspiration but write everything in your own words and cite it (Integrity: +4, Public Trust: +4, Sustainability: +3)
C) Paraphrase large sections without citing, figuring it's different enough (Integrity: -1, Public Trust: -2, Sustainability: -2)
D) Copy it with minor changes and submit it as your own work (Integrity: -4, Public Trust: -4, Sustainability: -4)
Question 3: Friends offer to help you forge a doctor's note to get an extension on a major project.
A) Decline and manage your time better or ask for a legitimate extension (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Consider it but ultimately decide against it due to the risks (Integrity: +3, Public Trust: +2, Sustainability: +2)
C) Accept the fake note but feel guilty about it (Integrity: -1, Public Trust: -2, Sustainability: -1)
D) Accept it and plan to use this strategy again in the future (Integrity: -3, Public Trust: -4, Sustainability: -4)
Question 4: One team member contributes nothing to the group project but asks to be included for credit.
A) Talk to the professor privately about the situation and let them decide fairly (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Confront the team member first and give them one last chance to contribute (Integrity: +4, Public Trust: +4, Sustainability: +4)
C) Include them but document what happened for your own records (Integrity: +1, Public Trust: 0, Sustainability: +1)
D) Include them to avoid conflict and move on (Integrity: -2, Public Trust: -2, Sustainability: -3)
Question 5: Your best friend asks to copy your homework because they had a family emergency.
A) Offer to help them understand the material but don't give answers (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +4, Sustainability: +5)
B) Give them your homework this once but make them promise not to ask again (Integrity: +2, Public Trust: +2, Sustainability: +1)
C) Let them copy it since it's just homework and they had a real emergency (Integrity: 0, Public Trust: -1, Sustainability: -2)
D) Give it to them and establish this as your regular arrangement (Integrity: -3, Public Trust: -3, Sustainability: -3)
Question 6: You discover you're receiving a scholarship meant for low-income students, but your family situation improved significantly.
A) Report the change immediately and return any funds you're no longer eligible for (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
