D) Agree since competitors do the same (Integrity: -4, Public Trust: -4, Sustainability: -4)
Question 12: You discover employees claiming false benefits; investigating would be costly and unpopular.
A) Investigate thoroughly and take appropriate action (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Address it privately with the individuals involved and give them a chance to make it right (Integrity: +4, Public Trust: +4, Sustainability: +4)
C) Tighten controls going forward but don't investigate past claims (Integrity: +1, Public Trust: 0, Sustainability: +1)
D) Ignore it to maintain employee morale (Integrity: -3, Public Trust: -3, Sustainability: -3)
Question 13: Installing proper safety equipment is expensive and would delay your product launch.
A) Delay the launch and install all required safety equipment (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Launch with current safety measures and add improvements incrementally (Integrity: +3, Public Trust: +3, Sustainability: +3)
C) Install minimum required equipment and hope for no incidents (Integrity: 0, Public Trust: -1, Sustainability: -1)
D) Skip it to meet deadlines and deal with issues if they arise (Integrity: -4, Public Trust: -5, Sustainability: -4)
Question 14: Your business partner makes discriminatory hiring decisions.
A) Confront them immediately and threaten to dissolve the partnership if it continues (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Implement formal hiring policies that prevent discrimination (Integrity: +4, Public Trust: +4, Sustainability: +4)
C) Handle your own hiring fairly but don't interfere with theirs (Integrity: 0, Public Trust: -2, Sustainability: -1)
D) Stay out of it since they handle HR (Integrity: -3, Public Trust: -4, Sustainability: -4)
Question 15: Your co-founder wants to exaggerate financial projections to attract investors.
A) Refuse and insist on accurate, conservative projections only (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Present realistic best-case scenarios with clear disclaimers about risks (Integrity: +4, Public Trust: +4, Sustainability: +4)
C) Allow some optimistic assumptions that might be achievable (Integrity: 0, Public Trust: -1, Sustainability: -1)
D) Agree to present inflated numbers to secure funding (Integrity: -4, Public Trust: -4, Sustainability: -4)
Question 16: After minor damage, someone suggests inflating the insurance claim.
A) Refuse and file an accurate claim for actual damages only (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Document everything carefully and let the insurance adjuster determine value (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +4)
C) Include some questionable items that might have been affected (Integrity: -1, Public Trust: -2, Sustainability: -2)
D) Maximize the claim to recover more than actual losses (Integrity: -4, Public Trust: -4, Sustainability: -4)
Question 17: Your CFO suggests booking revenue early to show better quarterly results.
A) Refuse and report accurate financial statements according to accounting standards (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Refuse and explain the long-term damage to credibility this would cause (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
C) Do it once to get through a difficult quarter (Integrity: -2, Public Trust: -3, Sustainability: -2)
D) Agree since it's technically revenue that will come eventually (Integrity: -4, Public Trust: -4, Sustainability: -4)
Question 18: A consultant suggests hiding assets before declaring bankruptcy.
A) Refuse completely and report the consultant for suggesting fraud (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Refuse and explore legitimate options like restructuring or debt negotiation (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
C) Consider it but ultimately decide against it due to legal risks (Integrity: +2, Public Trust: +1, Sustainability: +1)
D) Follow their advice to preserve personal wealth (Integrity: -5, Public Trust: -5, Sustainability: -5)
Question 19: A former employee of your competitor offers to sell you their trade secrets.
A) Refuse and report the attempted corporate espionage (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Refuse and compete based on your own innovations and strategy (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
C) Meet with them to hear what they have but don't commit (Integrity: 0, Public Trust: -1, Sustainability: -1)
D) Buy the information to gain competitive advantage (Integrity: -4, Public Trust: -4, Sustainability: -4)
Question 20: Competitors invite you to join a price-fixing agreement that would guarantee profits.
A) Refuse and report the cartel to antitrust authorities (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
B) Refuse and compete fairly on your own merits (Integrity: +5, Public Trust: +5, Sustainability: +5)
C) Listen to the proposal but ultimately decline participation (Integrity: +2, Public Trust: +1, Sustainability: +1)
D) Join since everyone else is already part of it (Integrity: -5, Public Trust: -5, Sustainability: -5)
SCORING SUMMARY
Maximum Possible Scores:
Each dimension: 100 points (20 questions × 5 points maximum per question)
Total possible: 300 points across all three dimensions
Score Calculation:
After answering all 20 questions, sum up the points for each dimension
Convert to percentage: (Total Points / 100) × 100
Calculate Overall Integrity Index: (Integrity % + Public Trust % + Sustainability %) / 3
Example: If a student scores:
Integrity: 65 points = 65%
Public Trust: 58 points = 58%
Sustainability: 72 points = 72%
Overall Integrity Index: (65 + 58 + 72) / 3 = 65%

